  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 13.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Gird yourselves, and lament, ye priests: howl, ye ministers of the altar: come, lie all night in sackcloth, ye ministers of my God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The invitation, or rather exhortation, here is to something more than lamentation and mourning; for, however natural in the circumstances, affliction itself could not avert or remove the calamity. They are urged, therefore, to repentance as well as lamentation. They were to assume the outward signs of the inward grace: they were to gird themselves with sackcloth, the outward symbol of their inward sorrow; next they were to enter the temple or house of God; they were to spend the night there in the attitude and garb of mourners; night and day they were to bewail their sins with humble, penitent, and contrite hearts. The priests are the persons first addressed, and that not only because, in discharge of their priestly functions as ministers of Jehovah and ministering at the altar, they had been specially touched by the present distress; but also because of their official position they were to present an example to the people whose leaders they were and on whose behalf they ministered (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 9:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"Do ye not know that they which minister about holy things live of the things of the temple? and they which wait at the altar are partakers with the altar?\"). Kimchi gives a correct exposition of this verse: \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Gird",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that is to say, gird on sackcloth, and he explains afterwards, pass the night in sackcloth, because even by night ye shall not remove the sackcloth from off you; perhaps Jehovah will have mercy upon you. And he says, 'ministers of the altar,' and adds, 'ministers of my God,' because the ministry was as the altar to God; and he connects the ministry to God - to the altar, as wherein they minister to Jehovah.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For the meat offering and the drink offering is withholden from the house of your God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This is the reason assigned for the urgent call to repentance; and it is much the same with that in the beginning of the ninth verse. Joel 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The affliction is not removed by mourning and lamentation, but only through repentance and supplication to the Lord, who can turn away all evil. The prophet therefore proceeds to call upon the priests to offer to the Lord penitential supplication day and night in the temple, and to call the elders and all the people to observe a day of fasting, penitence, and prayer; and then offers supplication himself to the Lord to have compassion upon them (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 1:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). From the motive assigned for this appeal, we may also see that a terrible drought had been associated with the devastation by the locusts, from which both man and beast had endured the most bitter suffering, and that Joel regarded this terrible calamity as a sign of the coming of the day of the Lord. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"Gird yourselves, and lament, ye priests; howl, ye servants of the altar; come, pass the night in sackcloth, ye servants of my God: for the meat-offering and drink-offering are withdrawn from the house of your God. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Sanctify a fast, call out an assembly, assemble the elders, all ye inhabitants of the land, at the house of Jehovah your God, and cry to Jehovah.\" From what follows we must supply bassaqqı̄m (with sackcloth) to chigrū (gird yourselves). Gird yourselves with mourning apparel, i.e., put it on (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 1:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In this they are to pass the night, to offer supplication day and night, or incessantly, standing between the altar and the porch (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 2:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"Servants of my God,\" i.e., of the God whose prophet I am, and from whom I can promise you a hearing. The reason assigned for this appeal is the same as for the lamentation in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joel 1:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". But it is not the priests only who are to pray incessantly to the Lord; the elders and all the people are to do the same. קדּשׁ צום, to sanctify a fast, i.e., to appoint a holy fast, a divine service of prayer connected with fasting. To this end the priests are to call an ‛ătsârâh, i.e., a meeting of the congregation for religious worship. ‛Atsârâh, or ‛ătsereth, πανήγυρις, is synonymous with מקרא קודשׁ in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 23:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see the exposition of that passage). In what follows, כּל־ישׁבי ה is attached ἀσυνδέτως to זקנים; and the latter is not a vocative, but an accusative of the object. On the other hand, בּית יהוה is an accus. loci, and dependent upon אספוּ. זעק, to cry, used of loud and importunate prayer. It is only by this that destruction can still be averted. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]